```

For example, a malicious XML document which is crafted using a nested series of internal entities, can be of a small size but designed to expand exponentially, forcing the parser to generate a final string that consumes a lot of memory:
```
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!DOCTYPE lolz [
 <!ENTITY lol "lol">
 <!ENTITY lol2 "&lol;&lol;&lol;&lol;&lol;&lol;&lol;&lol;&lol;&lol;">
 <!ENTITY lol3 "&lol2;&lol2;&lol2;&lol2;&lol2;&lol2;&lol2;&lol2;">
]>
<lolz>&lol3;</lolz>
```
When the parser expands the entities, it involves numerous calls to malloc/realloc to allocate more memory for the internal buffer. Because there are no limits, it continues to allocate memory until it consumes gigabytes of RAM, causing the application to crash or the entire system to become unresponsive, which causes a Denial-of-Service.

