[libarchive](https://www.libarchive.org/) is a portable, efficient C library that can read and write streaming archives in a variety of formats.

A logical error in the code in libarchive responsible for parsing multi-volume RAR archives can cause an unsigned integer overflow that may lead to a double free vulnerability. Specifically, the variable `rar->nodes`, which keeps track of the number of file parts in the archive, was an unsigned int (a 32-bit integer).

An attacker can craft a special multi-volume RAR archive with `UINT_MAX` (the maximum value a 32-bit unsigned int can hold) parts. To process the archive the server calls the function `archive_read_format_rar_seek_data` in libarchive, which triggers the function `read_header` that has the following code:

```
newsize = sizeof(*rar->dbo) * (rar->nodes + 1);
if ((newdbo = realloc(rar->dbo, newsize)) == NULL)
{
   archive_set_error(&a->archive, ENOMEM, "Couldn't allocate memory.");
   return (ARCHIVE_FATAL);
}
```

Since `rar->nodes` is an unsigned int and has the value of `UINT_MAX`, the increment causes an integer overflow, and the value of `newsize` wraps around to 0. When `realloc` gets zero as the second parameter, it might free the `rar->dbo` pointer and return `NULL`. The error handling mechanism of libarchive then propagates back with `ARCHIVE_FATAL` and triggers the cleanup function `archive_read_format_rar_cleanup`, which also calls to `free(rar->dbo)`, triggering the double free vulnerability.

This can result in memory corruption, enabling an attacker to execute arbitrary code or cause a denial-of-service.

